			<div class='cuisine-prompt'>
				<h2 class="h2-heading">Cuisine</h2>
				<p class="p-content">Peruvian cuisine varies across the region, however there are some staple foods that are common with many meals.  One of the foods Peru is most known for is its potatoes with there being over four thousand varieties!  Potatoes were historically and are currently grown widely across the region due to its ability to grow in harsh conditions.  With potatoes being as common as they are, they are served with almost every dish whether it be served as a side, commonly roasted in chunks or fried, or as part as a meal such as Causa Rellena, a layered mashed potato casserole with tuna and avocado, or Papa a la Huancaína which are boiled yellow potatoes served in a creamy, spicy Huancaína sauce.</p>
				<p class="p-content">Other staple foods of Peru include corn (especially the giant corn, Choclo), quinoa, and legumes.  Aside from the previous staple foods, much of the cuisine found across Peru also has its roots from other countries across the world.  Many of the more common staple foods originate from the Spanish.  Peru is also home to a sizable Chinese population which has resulted in a popular fusion cuisine known as Chifa.  Pizza has also become a largely consumed meal with pizzarias being found across many cities in Peru.</p>
			</div>


