			<div class='culture-prompt'>
				<h2 class="h2-heading">Culture</h2>
				<p class="p-content">Peru’s culture originates from the native Incas, Spanish conquistadors/settlers, as well as more recent immigrant groups such as Africans, Japanese, Chinese, and Europeans.  When it comes to arts and crafts, weaving is a common practice traditionally spun with llama or alpaca wool to make fabrics and clothing with intricate patterns and vibrant colors.  Continuing with the colorful theme, Retablos are colorful wooden altars depicting various sculpted figures and scenes usually religious related or originating from everyday activities.  Although painting has become more abstract in recent years, paintings were mostly related to religion as well as important battles and heroes of the story of Peru’s independence.</p>
				<p class="p-content">For traditional music, two of the most common instruments found in any composition include a drum and a panpipe.  For traditional music, Peruvian music generally relies on a percussion instrument, commonly a drum, and a wind instrument, commonly a panpipe or flute.  Many Peruvians, when it comes to sports, enjoy playing soccer, the national sport of Peru.  Towards the coast, however, surfing has also become a popular sport.</p>
			</div>


