				<h2 class="h2-heading">Geography</h2>
				<p class="p-content">With Peru situated along the Pacific coast as well as the Andes mountains, it offers a wide variety of geography.  Aside from its steep, snow tipped mountains and humid Pacific coast, Peru also shares much of its geography with the Amazon rainforest.  Another large portion of Peru’s geography is its high and flat plateaus.   Outside of the jungle, much of Peru is quite dry due to its location next to the Andes as well as the lack of moisture containing air masses from the Pacific.  Along the coast, the country is lined with coastal deserts that provide for some amazing natural sights. Peru, as well as Bolivia, is home to the highest navigable lake in the world, Lake Titicaca,  located 12,500ft above sea level.  With the wide variety of geographies across Peru, it is home to an incredible amount of biodiversity and as such has been labeled as a megadiverse country by the Conservation International organization.</p>
